value.value: An identifier for a contrast agent for which administration has ended.
An identifier for a contrast agent that was administered.
The amount of substance given a subject.
The amount of undiluted agent administered to a subject.
The speed at which an action is performed.
The amount of time elapsed during the administration of an agent.
The number of a specific beat.
The time measurement between the R wave of successive heartbeats as measured in milliseconds.
A multiplication factor used to obtain an estimated real-world value from a measured or calculated value.
Quantifiable estimate of the potential patency of a vessel in the absence of stenosis.
The minimum acceptable encoded velocity.
The maximum acceptable encoded velocity.
A thecoma of the ovary which may metastasize to another anatomic site. It is usually characterized by nuclear atypia and mitotic activity. Malignant thecomas are rare.
The amount of radiopharmaceutical given to a subject.
The total amount of radioisotope administered during a diagnostic or therapeutic event.
The total amount of radioactive material present in a syringe prior to administration, measured as counts per minute.
The amount of radioactive material remaining in a syringe after administration, measured as counts per minute.
The identity of the contrast agent.
A medication that is administered prior to a procedure.
A protocol for creating images or image-derived measurements.

The aromatic root of perennial herbs of Panax ginseng. Ginseng, used in traditional Chinese medicine and available as a nutritional supplement, is classified as an adaptogenic herb with multiple effects, many of them are regulatory in nature. It contains a complex mixture of saponins, ginsenosides and panaxosides. Although the mechanism of action is unclear, ginseng is reported to enhance the immune system and reduce fatigue.
A term used to denote that something is unchanging, not dynamic.
A nitrosourea with antineoplastic activity. Nimustine alkylates and crosslinks DNA, thereby causing DNA fragmentation, inhibition of protein synthesis, and cell death. (NCI05)
A neoplasm composed of at least two distinct cellular populations.
A bone prominence to which ligaments and tendons of the joints are attached.
A programming language and software environment for statistical computing and graphics.
An interpreted programming language for performing numerical computations for scientific computing.
Having been judged unacceptable.
Histone H4I protein (103 aa, ~11 kDa) is encoded by the human HIST1H4I gene. This protein plays a role in nucleating the formation of high order chromatin structures as a part of nucleosomes.
The collective identity of the entirety of carbohydrates (glycans) in an organism.
Put an end to a state or an activity.
A pathological hardening or thickening of tissue, especially that of the interstitial substance.

An effectively dimensionless measure of regional tracer uptake calculated as the activity concentration within a 2D region of interest (ROI) or 3D volume of interest (VOI) measured on a PET image (nCi1mL) / [injected dose (nCi) / body weight (g)].
An association that is asserted when there is a relationship or association between the therapeutic moiety and the endogenous gene product.
The set of vertebrae immediately caudal to the skull.
Those vertebrae between the ribs and the pelvis, L1-L5 in man.
The vertebrae of the thoracic spine, numbered one through twelve in man.
An instrument used for non-invasive determination of arterial blood pressure, generally consisting of an inflatable cuff and a pressure readout device, classically, a column of mercury.
An instrument for blood pressure monitoring consisting of a sphygmomanometer and a stethoscope to hear blood flow.

An instrument for blood pressure monitoring consisting of a sphygmomanometer and an electronic pressure sensor (transducer) that detects blood flow by the presence of ocillations in the cuff pressure.
A localized malignant neoplasm that arises in the bony skeleton or soft tissue. It is composed of clonal (malignant) plasma cells forming a tumor mass.
A medical instrument for listening to the sounds generated inside the body.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic polypoid growth in the middle ear.
A well differentiated, slow growing neuroepithelial neoplasm composed of neoplastic, mature ganglion cells.
A meningioma that affects the spinal cord.
A locally infiltrating, non-metastasizing angiomyxoma arising from the pelviperineal region.  It may recur following resection
